<HEADLINE>
<P>
SELLING DEFUNCT SAVINGS AND LOANS AT BARGAIN PRICES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Now that Charles Keating's Lincoln Savings and Loan scandal has disappeared 
from the headlines, along comes one to top it. It's Miami's CenTrust Bank 
bankruptcy that will also cost taxpayers over $2 billion (front page, June 24). 
</P>
<P>
Once again I was shocked to read about the criminal mismanagement of the 
savings and loans that it is estimated will cost us citizens $500 billion. 
</P>
<P>
David Paul, chairman of CenTrust, lived like a king for years and in effect 
sent the bills to us for payment. He helped himself to $16 million in pay 
during the last six years as a reward for his mismanagement. He had custom 
built a teak dock to house his $7-million yacht. He furnished his bank's 
executive dining room with Baccarat crystal goblets, Tiffany ashtrays, pounds 
of the most costly silver service and Limoges dinnerware. And that's only part 
of the excesses that we will be paying for in the years to come. 
</P>
<P>
It seems to be the same old story. Steal a loaf of bread and you go to jail. 
Steal millions or billions and you walk around free like Keating and Paul, not 
to mention the President's son, Neil Bush, who was involved in the Silverado 
S&amp;L heist in Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
It's time that white-collar bank robbers were punished to the fullest extent of 
the law. Pious words from President Bush on this subject are not enough. We are 
entitled to action. 
</P>
<P>
LAWRENCE KANE 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
