<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY NEWS ROUNDUP: COUNTYWIDE; 
</P>
<P>
PANEL SEARCHES FOR WASP RELEASE SITES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Psyche Pascual 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Ventura County Agricultural Commission is looking for potential sites to 
release biological enemies of the ash whitefly, officials said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
Deputy Agricultural Commissioner Ann McClure said the agency is compiling a 
list of areas in the county that meet the state Department of Food and 
Agriculture's requirements for breeding the predator, a stingless wasp that is 
harmless to humans, but that attacks the whitefly. 
</P>
<P>
Potential sites must have more than one tree present to ensure that the wasps 
can live there year-round, McClure said. Homeowners must agree not to spray the 
tree or cut it down. 
</P>
<P>
State agricultural officials have said they plan to release 250 wasps at each 
of four as yet unidentified sites. Psyche Pascual 
</P>
</TEXT>
