<P>
8,000 JOBS MAY BE LOST TO SAVE OWL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Reconsidering the extent of its decision earlier this week, the state 
Department of Forestry said as many as 8,000 jobs may be lost when it expands 
protection of spotted-owl habitat to private lands. 
</P>
<P>
The rules, similar to those regulating national forests, originally were 
expected to cost no more than 1,900 jobs. The rules forbid logging that damages 
owl nests or reduces owl habitat. The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service recently 
declared the northern spotted owl, which lives in valuable old-growth forests, 
to be threatened with extinction because of heavy logging. This forced the 
state to take measures to protect the bird. 
</P>
