</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Eye Drug Recalled: The Food and Drug Administration is recalling the 
prescription eye drug Opticrom, a solution of cromolyn sodium sold in 
10-milliliter bottles, citing the threat of potentially blinding bacterial 
infection. FDA officials said Fisons Corp. of Rochester, N.Y., is voluntarily 
pulling the drug off the market after tests showed that two lots -- stamped 
KF7A and KF35V -- may be contaminated with bacteria that can cause 
vision-threatening infections in people whose eyes are scratched or damaged. 
Bottles with those two lot numbers should be returned to pharmacies, the FDA 
said. 
</P>
