309 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
SO. BAPTIST UNIT FIRES ANTI-SMUT SALVO IN NEA DISPUTE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALLAN PARACHINI, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A policy committee of the 14.9 million-member Southern Baptist Convention has 
told members of Congress the denomination will call for abolition of the 
National Endowment for the Arts unless strict controls are enacted barring 
federal funds for "obscene, highly offensive, morally repugnant and 
sacrilegious art." 
</P>
<P>
The Baptist group -- the nation's largest Protestant denomination -- became the 
first major church body to formally demand strict and religion-oriented 
controls over the NEA since a controversy broke out last year over endowment 
funding of controversial artists and artworks. 
</P>
<P>
The new action was taken by the convention's Nashville-based Christian Life 
Commission, which is empowered to take positions on behalf of the entire 
denomination, according to commission spokesman Louis Moore. Moore said the 
commission sent letters to every member of Congress on June 10. 
</P>
<P>
"Clearly, those who are responsible for awarding grants at the NEA have 
(funded), and will continue to fund, activities which most Americans find 
highly offensive," said commission executive director Richard D. Land. Land 
noted that the annual meeting of the Southern Baptist Convention in New Orleans 
last month had been unable to act on the anti-NEA resolution because the issue 
came up for action the last day of the meeting, when a quorum was absent. 
</P>
<P>
"We have no doubt that if the convention had been given the opportunity to act 
upon this resolution, it would have overwhelmingly approved it," Land said. 
</P>
<P>
The commission's letter to Congress complained about photographs by the late 
Robert Mapplethorpe and Andres Serrano -- the images that set off the 
controversy last year. It also questioned the propriety of NEA grants to other 
artists whose work has been the subject of bitter attacks by right-wing 
religious organizations and conservative politicians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
