<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: COUNTYWIDE; 
</P>
<P>
CONTINUANCE URGED FOR WELFARE FUNDS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CATHERINE GEWERTZ 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Frustrated by the budget stalemate in Sacramento, Supervisor Don R. Roth wrote 
a letter to Gov. George Deukmejian asking for his help in bringing about an 
agreement that will guarantee a continued flow of money to Orange County's 
welfare recipients. 
</P>
<P>
In a letter written Thursday, Roth said the budget standoff means that $37.1 
million in state funds intended for Orange County for the month of July are 
being withheld, including $19.1 million to cover local welfare checks. 
</P>
<P>
The state Senate approved a $52-billion-plus budget Tuesday, but its tax and 
fee increases set it up for likely defeat in the Assembly. 
</P>
<P>
Members of a joint Senate-Assembly budget committee took up the measure Friday, 
but by afternoon they were divided and talks had stalled. 
</P>
<P>
Roth said the county's proposed budget includes provisions to continue funding 
for critical programs for a while. 
</P>
<P>
But he complained that the county is pinched unfairly in a state budget impasse 
because it is required to operate entitlement programs without state funds. 
</P>
<P>
"This current situation simply highlights the lack of state concern in 
underfunding its mandates and withholding what limited funding is required to 
support the entitlement programs," Roth wrote. 
</P>
<P>
He said he is particularly concerned because of the increasing conflict between 
growing program demands and the decrease in state funding. 
</P>
<P>
"I believe the state budgeting system must address the appropriate and timely 
funding of the programs which it requires the County of Orange to operate," 
Roth said. 
</P>
<P>
Roth suggested that the state could solve the problem by adopting a budget 
provision to ensure continuation of a current year's aid into the next fiscal 
year if necessary, or by establishing a special trust fund to cover such aid if 
lawmakers must debate the budget into the next fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
He also suggested that legislators draft a budget that includes July payments 
in the prior fiscal year's budget so that all mandated programs are covered 
while the new budget is debated. CATHERINE GEWERTZ 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
