<HEADLINE>
<P>
BASTILLE DAY: TIME TO STORM THOSE FRENCH EATERIES; 
</P>
<P>
RESTAURANTS: CAN-CAN, MUSIC AND THAT WORLD-FAMOUS CUISINE WILL BE FEATURED 
TODAY THROUGHOUT ORANGE COUNTY AS THE SPIRIT OF LIBERTY, FRATERNITY AND 
GASTRONOMY OVERTAKE THE POPULACE. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BEVERLY BUSH SMITH 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Special menus, accordions, can-can dancers -- you can count on French 
restaurateurs to pull out all the stops for Bastille Day today. Here are a few 
options for your celebration of the 1789 attack and capture of the French 
prison fortress. 
</P>
<P>
Bastille Day commemorates the triumph of the populace, the bourgeois, according 
to Marica Hefti of Le Medi in Newport Beach. So she and her chef-husband Walter 
Ruttiman will serve from big pots of moules mariniere, the traditional mussels 
dish, on the restaurant's patio at bourgeois prices -- from $1.75. Also 
available outdoors: seafood salad and strawberries with black pepper. Inside, 
diners can sit down to a dinner of duck Bigarade (with orange), French onion 
soup and chocolate mousse, all for $14.95. The same menu will be served at 
lunchtime, from 11:30 to 3 p.m.; and dinner, from 6 until "whatever," according 
to Marica. Reservations: (714) 675-4904. 
</P>
<P>
Can-can dancers liven the festivities at several restaurants, including La Vie 
en Rose in Brea, which will also present a magician. A special multi-course 
dinner, priced at $50, will be served from 6 to 10 p.m. Reservations: (714) 
529-8333. 
</P>
<P>
The celebration began Friday at the Bouzy Rouge in Newport Beach with a French 
fashion show. Tonight's the night for the can-can dancers, an accordionist, 
door prize drawings and the opening of a methuselum (that's eight bottles' 
worth) of champagne. Service from the Parisian bistro menu begins at 6 p.m. 
Reservations: (714) 675-3440. 
</P>
<P>
At Chanteclair in Irvine, chef Byron Gemmell, will present a nine-course menu 
de degustation complemented by four wines. It's $85 per person plus tax and 
gratuity. Reservations for tonight or Saturday: (714) 752-8001. 
</P>
<P>
Accordionists set the mood for celebrating a la Francaise at several other 
restaurants, including Pascal in Newport Beach, during its festivities tonight. 
The Provencale country dinner includes four courses, all seasoned with 
Provencale herbs, of course, with a choice of such entrees as rabbit, duck and 
grilled fish. There will be wine on the tables, and the tab is $39 per person, 
exclusive of tax and tip. Reservations: (714) 752-0107. 
</P>
<P>
An accordion player will also entertain at Cafe Francais in Orange. Owner 
Jacques Duc also promises a six-course dinner, highlighting feuillete of 
scallops with caramelized onions, confit of duck with cloves and fresh 
rosemary. The tab is $36.50. Reservations: (714) 998-6051. 
</P>
<P>
In Huntington Beach, at his new Voila, the very French Yves Briee will add 
strictly French specials to his menu and pour a complimentary glass of 
champagne for each diner. Incidentally, the restaurant is now open for dinner 
only. Reservations: (714) 841-1166. 
</P>
<P>
LaFayette in Buena Park celebrates with a five-course Bastille dinner. There 
will be appetizer and soup-salad choices; salmon in lobster sauce; a selection 
of meat courses and imported cheese and pastries. It's $40 a person. 
Reservations: (714) 537-5011. 
</P>
</TEXT>
