773 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
NONTOXIC PEST CONTROL BECOMES BIG BUSINESS; 
</P>
<P>
EXTERMINATORS: TALLON USES NOVEL APPROACHES AND AVOIDS SPRAYING POISONS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The best way to zap termites, said exterminator Jay Tallon, is to "freeze their 
little buns off." 
</P>
<P>
That's just one of several novel ways Tallon and his brother, Joe, have devised 
to kill household pests without using poisons that may endanger pets, plants or 
homeowners. And it's become big business. 
</P>
<P>
"We have what the consumer wants today. They don't want you to go out there and 
spray toxic chemicals on everything in sight," Jay Tallon said. 
</P>
<P>
Tallon Termite &amp; Pest Control, based in Redondo Beach, has developed an 
arsenal that eschews toxic pesticides in favor of high-tech devices and 
old-fashioned common sense. 
</P>
<P>
Included are a "bug vacuum" for swooshing up spiders and other creepy crawlies, 
a steam-based "flea machine" for infested carpets, glue boards for catching 
mice and a tiny electric fence that keeps home foundations off limits to 
multiple-footed outsiders. 
</P>
<P>
The Tallons have also perfected a way to literally look inside the walls of 
homes and pinpoint where termites may be munching away. Using fiber-optic 
instruments, pest-control experts peek inside those hard-to-reach places to 
find the unwanted denizens. 
</P>
<P>
The voracious termites tend to cluster, Tallon said. Normally, they will be 
found in just a couple of walls, congregated in three or four of the timber 
support studs. 
</P>
<P>
The first step in getting rid of them is to probe with fiber-optic instruments 
to pinpoint their location. Then a dime-sized hole is drilled at the bottom of 
the wall and another at the top. Liquid nitrogen is pumped through the holes 
into the inaccessible areas, freezing the termites. 
</P>
<P>
"We freeze their little buns off," Tallon said with a grin, noting that 
termites are killed by the cold, which reaches minus-20 degrees, and not by the 
liquid nitrogen itself. 
</P>
<P>
"Termites will tell you they're 98% water," a Tallon radio ad says. "When we're 
done with 'em, they are 200% frozen. The idea is dead simple. We freeze 
termites instead of fumigate them." 
</P>
<P>
Eighty percent of the air humans breathe consists of nitrogen, and the freezing 
process is environmentally safe, Tallon said. When the temperature returns to 
normal, the liquid nitrogen evaporates. 
</P>
<P>
Called the Blizzard System, the eradication process is registered with the 
Environmental Protection Agency, and Tallon said the company is the only one in 
the nation using the super-cold approach for excising termites. 
</P>
<P>
But some species of termites succumb more easily to excess heat than cold, and 
the Tallons last year began marketing a companion system called the HeatWave. 
</P>
<P>
Using a convection heating system, heat strips are applied to the wood 
requiring treatment and then the electricity is turned on. About 30 minutes are 
required for the heat to penetrate to the center of the wood and reach 135 
degrees. The termites die within a minute or two. 
</P>
<P>
Tallon is applying its non-traditional, environmentally safe methods toward the 
destruction of all types of household pests, including ants, roaches, spiders, 
fleas, mice and rats. 
</P>
<P>
The company, which saw sales jump from $85,000 a month in 1987 to $700,000 per 
month this year, is expanding into the San Francisco Bay Area this summer and 
is opening offices in Florida and Hawaii. 
</P>
<P>
"We hope to be throughout the United States over the next five years," Tallon 
said. 
</P>
<P>
The traditional method of tenting -- enclosing a home and moving everyone out 
before spraying for bugs with pesticides -- is becoming increasingly 
distasteful in this era of growing environmental awareness, he said. 
</P>
<P>
"We don't want to become spray jockeys," he added. "We've started a pilot 
program for comprehensive, non-conventional pest control." 
</P>
<P>
Tallon's war on fleas features a "flea machine" that steams the carpet and 
kills the adult wingless hoppers hiding in the fibers. It also includes a 
nontoxic "birth-inhibitor" spray that prevents young insects from matriculating 
through a complete life cycle. 
</P>
<P>
Rodents get no respite from the Tallons either. The company's crews use 
electrical barriers, consisting of a single strand of wire and low-voltage 
batteries, to prevent mice, rats and roaches from coming inside the house. 
</P>
<P>
"We first exclude them from the structure," Tallon said. "We trap the ones in 
the house with mice glue boards. They have a gummy substance on them that 
attracts the mice to it, and (they) go and get stuck and they suffocate." 
</P>
<P>
Then there's the "Bugvac" for spiders. "We vacuum all the spiders up," Tallon 
said. "We go outside as well as in the home and vacuum the corners and areas 
where spiders are." 
</P>
<P>
The cost of treating a 2,000-square-foot house via the Tallon method ranges 
between $1,000 and $1,500, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
