<HEADLINE>
<P>
DIVIDE JOB TO CONQUER BUILDING OF A PARTITION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By A. J. HAND, A. J. Hand writes for the Los Angeles Times Syndicate. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Although the trend in home design is toward open, undivided spaces, there are 
still times when you may actually want to divide big spaces up into smaller 
ones. Building a walk-in closet is one reason. So is adding a darkroom or maybe 
a soundproof music room. 
</P>
<P>
Whatever the reason, the thing that gets the job done is the partition, a 
simple structure that any homeowner with a saw and hammer should be able to 
build. 
</P>
<P>
Before you build a partition, draw it out to scale. This will help you 
visualize the job and will make it easy to compile a shopping list for lumber. 
</P>
<P>
At the very minimum, you'll need 2-by-4 top and bottom plates, plus 2-by-4 
studs spaced every 16 inches on center. If you're framing for a door, you'll 
need two or three extra studs for the trimmers, plus a six-foot 2-by-6 and a 
scrap of half-inch plywood for the header. 
</P>
<P>
The door itself? A simple prehung flush door is the easiest to install. These 
come in a variety of widths from 18 to 36 inches. A 30-incher is a good 
all-around size. 
</P>
<P>
You'll also need a few pounds of 16-penny nails and a few pounds of eightpenny 
nails to put everything together. 
</P>
<P>
You have a choice of two ways to frame the wall. One is to assemble the whole 
thing lying flat, then stand it up and nail it in place. The other is to build 
the wall in place. Which is better? 
</P>
<P>
Building flat on the floor is usually easier. Everything is easy to reach, and 
you can nail through the plates into the ends of the studs rather than 
toenailing. But, if your walls, floor and ceiling are irregular, a preassembled 
wall may not fit properly without a lot of shimming and adjusting. Building the 
wall in place makes more sense under these conditions. 
</P>
<P>
For a flat assembly, start by marking the location of the proposed wall on the 
floor. If possible, locate the partition so you can nail the top plate into the 
ceiling joists. If this isn't possible, you'll have to cut 14 1/2-inch lengths 
of the same lumber used for the joists (usually 2-by-8 stock) and nail them in 
crosswise every 16 to 20 inches between existing joists. This will give you 
something to nail your top plate to. 
</P>
<P>
Back down on the floor, cut your top and bottom plates to length and mark off 
the positions of your studs, 16 inches on center. Keep this 16-inch interval 
constant, even if a door opening interrupts the flow. 
</P>
<P>
Next, measure your floor-to-ceiling height and subtract three inches. This 
gives you the length of your studs. Cut them all to this length and secure them 
to the top and bottom plates, using a pair of 16-penny nails through the plate 
and into each end of the stud. 
</P>
<P>
If you are framing in a door, size the rough opening 2 1/2 inches wider than 
your door and one inch higher. This will give you room to shim and adjust the 
door frame properly later on. Next, nail together a header from two layers of 
2-by-6 with a layer of half-inch plywood sandwiched between. Cut this to length 
and nail it in place with 16-penny nails. Then cut your trimmer studs to 
length, nail them in place, and finally, add the little cripples above the 
header. 
</P>
<P>
Now you can stand the wall up. Make sure the bottom plate is positioned 
properly and tack it in place with a couple of nails. If you are working on a 
concrete floor, use concrete nails. Carefully plumb the wall, using a 
carpenter's level to make sure it is dead vertical in both directions. If the 
wall is a bit short in spots, you may have to slip shims between the top plate 
and the ceiling. A piece of cedar shingle works well. 
</P>
<P>
When everything is positioned to your satisfaction, nail through the top plate 
into the ceiling joist or your previously installed blocking, and nail through 
the bottom plate into the floor. But don't nail through the section of bottom 
plate running across your door opening. Instead, saw this section out and throw 
it away. You can now install your door, and finish off with drywall or 
paneling. 
</P>
<P>
For in-place assembly, start by cutting top and bottom plates to length and 
marking them off for proper stud placement. Install the top plate first, 
nailing through it into the ceiling joists or into blocking. Once the top plate 
is in place, install the bottom plate, locating it directly beneath the top 
plate by using a plumb bob. Fasten the bottom plate in place by nailing it to 
the floor. If you will be framing in a door, do not nail the bottom plate down 
in the area of the opening. 
</P>
<P>
Once both plates are in, measure each stud individually to fit its space. 
Install the studs by toenailing with your eightpenny nails, driving in a pair 
of nails from each side of each stud, both top and bottom. 
</P>
<P>
Frame your door opening as described above. Then cut out the section of bottom 
plate spanning the door opening and you are ready to install the door and 
finish off the wall. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
BUILDING MATERIALS; INTERIOR DESIGN; WALLS 
</P>
